earrow &amp;\ S_0 &amp; &amp; \ &amp; \searrow &amp; \ &amp; &amp; dS_0 \end{matrix}\quad egin{matrix} &amp; &amp; C_u\ &amp; 
earrow &amp;\ C_0 &amp; &amp; \ &amp; \searrow &amp; \ &amp; &amp; C_d \end{matrix}
onumber \] <p>Consider the above value tree</p> <p>Portfolio A: \(x\) stocks + \(\$y\) T-bills = Portfolio B: Call option</p> <p>No arbitrage condition tells us that the two portfolio should have the same payoff as well as the same price $$ xuS_0+yR=C_u\ xdS_0+yR=C_d
onumber $$ Here \(R=1+r_f\)​</p> <p>We can solve for \(x\) and \(y\), then we know \(C_0=xS_0+y\) $$  egin{aligned} C_0&amp;= rac1R\left( rac{R-d}{u-d}C_u+ rac{u-R}{u-d}C_dight)\ &amp;= rac1R(qC_u+(1-q)C_d) \end{aligned}
onumber $$ Here we define the risk neutral probability \(q=(R-d)/(u-d)\), note that we always have \(d&lt;R&lt;u\) (yes?)</p> <p>The underlying asset has probability of \(q\) to increase in value and \((1-q)\) to decrease in value (This is NOT the real probability!)</p>

